Mount_Pleasant_Cemetery,_Toronto
Mount Pleasant Cemetery is a cemetery located in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.In the early 19th century, the only authorized cemeteries within the city of Toronto (then known as York) were limited to the members of either the Catholic Church or the of England. Deceased citizens who did not belong to either of these Christian denominations had no choice but to find burial arrangements outside of the city. In 1873, a new cemetery available to all citizens was conceived. Originally a  farm, on the far outskirts of Toronto, Mount Pleasant Cemetery opened on November 4, 1876 with more than twelve miles (19 km) of carriage drives along rolling hills and ponds. Pleasant Road was later constructed to pass through the centre of the cemetery and is named after this cemetery. With the growth in population, today the cemetery is located in the centre of the city. While the watercourses have since been filled in, the cemetery still has many miles of walking paths, interspersed with fountains, statues, botanical gardens, and rare and distinct trees.As the final resting place of more than 168,000 persons, Mount Pleasant Cemetery contains remarkable architecture amongst its many monuments. The cemetery was designated a National Historic Site of Canada in 2000.(Mount Pleasant Cemetery,  Directory of Designations of National Historic Significance of Canada)(Mount Pleasant Cemetery, National Register of Historic Places)Mount Pleasant Visitation Centrethumb|270px|right|Visitation CentreCompleted in the Fall of 2009, the Mount Pleasant Visitation Centre is a new building built on the cemetery grounds designed to provide visitation space, chapel services, and reception space. The brick building is approximately 2,200 square meters in total size, with an outdoor 80 car parking lot.(http://www.visitationcentre.ca/MP_new-visit.html Accessed October 2nd, 2009)The cemetery began planning the building as early as 2004, but disputes with the City of Toronto, local ratepayer associations, and the Municipal Board all delayed the project. Changes were made as a result of this process, most notably vehicle access is now through the cemetery grounds only, not directly from Moore Avenue.(http://www.visitationcentre.ca/MP_design.html Accessed October 2nd, 2009)(http://www.moorepark.org/ Accessed October 2nd, 2009) Notable interments Veterans* William George Billy Barker, VC, DSO & Bar, MC & Two Bars (18941930), LCOL, 201 Squadron, RAF. World War I flying ace, Victoria Cross recipient* George Fraser Kerr, VC, MC & Bar, MM (18951929), CAPT, 3rd battalion (Toronto) Central Ontario Regiment, CEF. World War I Victoria Cross recipientTitanic* Godfrey Peuchen Lieutenant-Colonel (April 18, 1859  December 7, 1929) was a Canadian businessman and RMS Titanic survivor. He was also a WWI veteran.Medicine Personalities* Banting (18911941)  &  Charles Best (18991978), co-discoverers of insulin * Harmer (18801934), prominent Canadian/American nurse* Smillie Robertson (18781981), Canadas first female surgeonMusic Personalities* Gimby (19181998) Writer of the 67 theme: Ca-na-da* Gould (19321982), musician, pianist, composer, musical theorist* Heintzman, & Co. piano manufacturer* Muir (18301906), author of Maple Leaf Forever (1867), Canadas early (unofficial) National Anthem* Mulgrew, Core Logo lead singer and frontman (Fictional Character)BusinesspeopleImage:Aaa massy.jpg|thumb|270px|The Family crypt, designed by Lennox in the Romanesque Revival style.* Ernest Ames (18671934), stockbroker, founder of A.E. Ames & Co.* J. Billes (19021995), cofounder of Tire* Montegu Black II (19111976), president of Breweries* James Boylen (19071970) mining magnate, racehorse owner* Albertus Cox (18401914), businessman, Senator* T. Davies (18491916), businessman, racehorse owner* Eaton (18341907), department store magnate* Henry Gundy (18801951), stockbroker, co-founder of Gundy Inc.* Henry R. Jackman (1900-1979), businessman and politician, father of Governor Henry N.R. Jackman* Edward Kemp (18581929