Deering,_Alaska
footnotes                 Deering (Ipnatchiaq in Iupiaq) is a city in the Northwest Arctic Borough in the U.S. state of Alaska. It is located on a sandy spit on the Peninsula where the River flows into Sound,  southwest of Kotzebue.  As of the 2000 census, the population was 136. , the village includes a community hall, a clinic run by the U.S. Public Health Service, a post office, a church, two stores, and a National Guard armory.CultureThe inhabitants are primarily Iupiat Eskimo. The people are active in subsistence. The sale or importation of alcohol is banned in the village.HistoryThe village was established in 1901 as a supply station for interior gold mining near the historic Malemiut Eskimo village of Inmachukmiut. The name probably comes from the schooner Abbie M. Deering, which was present in the area at that time; see Abbie M. Deering. Deering incorporated as a second-class city in 1970. It also has a village council, organized under the Reorganization Act of 1934.GeographyDeering is located at  (66.075713, -162.718229).According to the States Census Bureau, the village has a total area of , of which,  of it is land and  of it (2.28%) is water.DemographicsAs of the census of 2000, there were 136 people, 42 households, and 28 families residing in the village. The population density was 26.5 people per square mile (10.2/km). There were 61 housing units at an average density of 11.9 per square mile (4.6/km). The racial makeup of the city was 93.38% Native American (Iupiat), 5.88% White, and 0.74% from two or more races.There were 42 households out of which 40.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 21.4% were married couples living together, 33.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 31.0% were non-families. 23.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.24 and the average family size was 3.90.In the village the age distribution of the population shows 39.7% under the age of 18, 6.6% from 18 to 24, 28.7% from 25 to 44, 17.6% from 45 to 64, and 7.4% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 27 years. For every 100 females there were 109.2 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 115.8 males.The median income for a household in the village was $33,333, and the median income for a family was $43,438. Males had a median income of $26,875 versus $25,625 for females. The capita income for the village was $11,000. None of the families but 5.8% of the population were below the line. No one under the age of 18 or over 64 were living below the poverty line.The Abbie M. DeeringA first-hand account written by Captain James D. Winchester and published in 1900 tells that the Abbie M. Deering was bought by a company of twenty men who wanted to sail to the Alaskan Gold Fields during the Gold Rush. They left Massachusetts in November 1897, passed through the Straits of Magellan, and arrived at San Francisco five months later, where they sold the ship. Records kept by the Management Service of the Department of the Interior show the schooner did make it to Alaska, where it was lost in the Islands in September 1903.Kiplings 1897 novel Courageous mentions the Abbie M. Deering by name.References(External links*Maniilaq Association web page for Deering(Alaska)(Alaska)(Alaska)ik:Ipnatchiaq(Alaska)mrj:(Alaska)(Alasca)Alaska(Alaska)Alaska(Alaska)
