Emmett,_Idaho
 Emmett is a city in Gem County, Idaho, States. The population was 5,490 at the 2000 census; it was estimated to have risen to 6,341 by 2007.()  It is the seat and the only city in the county.  Emmett is part of the Boise City&ndash;Nampa, Idaho Metropolitan Statistical Area.HistoryRising some 5,906 feet, Squaw Butte, named by native Americans who used this area as their winter resort, stands at the north end of the valley. The Payette River was named after Francois Payette, who was put in charge of Fort Boise in 1818 and traveled through the area. Permanent settlement began in the early 1860s, after gold discoveries in the Boise Basin brought people over the established stage and pack train routes. Two of these trails joined at the Payette River north of the present river bridge in Emmett.Originally called Emmettville, it was primarily a post office named after Emmett Cahalan, the son of Tom Cahalan, an early settler of the area. The post office was later moved but retained the name. A few years later the ville was dropped and the post office and town became simply Emmett. In 1883 James Wardwell had the town platted, and in 1900 the town was incorporated as Emmett. Later, in March of 1902, the Idaho Northern railroad came to the valley. (http://www.gemcountymuseum.org/history-railroad.html, Gem County Historical Society, Accessed 2011-7-20)After the closing of the mines in 1906, the power lines were extended to Emmett. A series of irrigation projects made it possible for more rapid expansion of the town as the major service center for a farming and fruit-growing valley. In the early 1900s fruit packers adopted the label of Gem of Plenty because of the fertility of the valley. During the mining era the valley was known as the garden for the mining regions.(http://www.emmettid-realestate.com/history.htm, United Country Musick & Sons Auctions / Real Estate Accessed 2011-7-11)Until 2001, the city was home to a Cascade manufacturing facility.(Boise Cascade Announces Closure of Plywood, Lumber Operations in Idaho, Boise Cascade, 2001-02-13.  Accessed 2009-03-31.) The Black Canyon diversion dam on the River, built in the early 1920s, is east of the city.(USBR - Black Canyon Dam)GeographyEmmett is located at  (43.872834, -116.494902).According to the States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of , all of it land.The city is located south of the River, at an elevation of 2362 feet (720 m) above sea level.Demographics11 memorial at Freezeout HillAs of the census of 2000, there were 5,490 people, 2,095 households, and 1,412 families residing in the city.  The density was 3,022.5 people per square mile (1,164.7/km).  There were 2,264 housing units at an average density of 1,246.4 per square mile (480.3/km).  The racial makeup of the city was 90.60% White, 0.07% African American, 0.75% Native American, 0.44% Asian, 0.15% Pacific Islander, 5.79% from other races, and 2.20% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 11.57% of the population.There were 2,095 households out of which 34.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 50.5% were married couples living together, 12.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 32.6% were non-families. 28.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.55 and the average family size was 3.13.In the city the population was spread out with 28.4% under the age of 18, 9.1% from 18 to 24, 26.3% from 25 to 44, 18.4% from 45 to 64, and 17.8% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females there were 90.6 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 85.5 males.The median income for a household in the city was $26,480, and the median income for a family was $34,663. Males had a median income of $30,598 versus $19,088 for females. The capita income for the city was $13,027.  About 16.3% of families and 17.8% of the population were below the line, including 23.4% of those under age 18 and 16.5% of those age 65 or over.Population history*2007 estimate - 6,341()* 2000 - 5,940* 1990 - 4,601(Moffatt, Riley.  Population History of Western U.S. Cities & Towns, 1850-1990.  Lanham: Scarecrow, 1996, 92.)* 1980 - 4,605* 1970 - 3,945* 1960 - 3,769* 1950 - 3,067* 1940 - 3,203* 1930 - 2,763* 1920 - 2,204* 1910 - 1,351* 1900 - 508* 1890 - 197TransportationEmmett is served by State Highway 52, which connects it with Horseshoe Bend to the east and Payette to the west, and by State Highway 16, which connects it with Boise to the south.(Rand McNally.  The Road Atlas 09. Chicago: McNally, 2009, p. 31.)ClimateEmmett experiences a climate (Kppen BSk) with cold, moist winters and hot, dry summers.dateMarch 2011Notable peopleAward winner Paul was born in Emmett.()References(External links* Chamber of Commerce - Emmett and Gem Countybg:(Idaho)(Idaho)(Idaho)fr:EmmettIdahoIdaho(Idaho)(Idaho)IdahoIdaho(Idaho)
110902
Moweaqua,_Illinois
Moweaqua is a village in Shelby County, Illinois, States, and partly in County, Illinois. The population was 1,831 at the 2010 census.GeographyDecatur is located at .According to the States Census Bureau, the village has a total area of 1.1 square miles (2.9 km), all of it land.DemographicsAs of the census of 2000, there were 1,923 people, 772 households, and 541 families residing in the village.  The density was 1,720.0 people per square mile (662.9/km).  There were 819 housing units at an average density of 732.6 per square mile (282.3/km).  The racial makeup of the village was 99.17% White, 0.05% Native American, 0.26% Asian, 0.21% from other races, and 0.31% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 0.57% of the population.There were 772 households out of which 32.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.9% were married couples living together, 8.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.9% were non-families. 27.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.38 and the average family size was 2.90.In the village the population was spread out with 23.9% under the age of 18, 7.5% from 18 to 24, 24.8% from 25 to 44, 21.7% from 45 to 64, and 22.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females there were 82.6 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 80.1 males.The median income for a household in the village was $40,114, and the median income for a family was $48,750. Males had a median income of $38,750 versus $21,974 for females. The capita income for the village was $18,195.  About 7.3% of families and 11.9% of the population were below the line, including 18.3% of those under age 18 and 9.0% of those age 65 or over.EducationMoweaqua is served by the Central A&M School District, which was established in 1993, and also includes the city of Assumption as well as the nearby rural areas.  Central A&M High School (grades 9-12) and Gregory Intermediate School (3-5) are located in one building on the northern edge of Moweaqua.  The high school enrollment is approximately 300 students, and their teams are known as the Raiders. The Girls Varsity Basketball team went to the state competition in 2008 and won third place.HistoryFrom 1891 until 1935, Moweaqua was the site of a gassy mine that mined coal from Pennsylvanian strata.  On the morning of December 24, 1932, fifty-four coal miners, the entire day shift, were killed by a methane explosion in the Moweaqua coal mine disaster.  The incident occurred on the morning of Eve, and one of the deceased miners, Tom Jackson, had been scheduled to play Claus in a party to be held that evening for his fellow townspeople.  The tragic explosion, together with the election in the previous month (November 1932) of the pro-labor Seventy-Third Congress, led to the pasasge of mine safety legislation and the phaseout of open-flame carbide miners lanterns in United States coal mines.  The Moweaqua Coal Mine Museum opened in 1986 to commemorate local coal miners, especially the victims of this disaster.()The 2009 movie The Informant starring Damon was partially filmed in Moweaqua.()  The plot of the movie is based on the ADM price fixing scandal which occurred during the 1990s.  The scandal centered around ADM Vice President Whitacre who lived in Moweaqua during the time.  Filming reportedly took place at the former Whitacre residence as well as the local restaurant now known as The Hog Trough Too which Whitacre frequented while living there. The former Whitacre residence, located approximately 1 mile west of the Moweaqua city limits, was originally owned by the step-grandfather of former ABC president James E. Duffy. Mr. Duffy lived there for a time during his boyhood, and his time there, and his formative relationship with his step-grandfather, was documented in his 1997 autobiography, Stay Tuned.Local Businesses-Papa Ronnies Pizza & More-Halls Jewelry and Gifts -Moweaqua Foods -Moweaqua Bowl and Cafe-Timis Tours-Old Firehouse Auction -Ace Auto Repair-Gene Lower Insurance & Real Estate-Dollar General-Moweaqua Farmers MarketReferences(External links* Official Site - Moweaqua.Net* Mining More in Moweaqua 1889-1940ca:Moweaqua(Illinois)Ilinwanl:Moweaquapt:Moweaquavo:Moweaqua
